  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Sustainable transformation of livelihoods in 13 rural communities in the dry corridor in Jinotega</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project will be implemented by Caritas Jinotega in 13 poor communities in the municipality of Jinotega with the participation of around 265 families. This will be phase 3 of the project which is looking to scale up some successful initiatives which started in phase 1and2 (2010-2013, and 2014-2016). This municipality is located in a region with high vulnerability to natural disasters and climate change. These communities are located in an agro-ecological zone called the dry corridor, which is characterized by poor rainfall and long dry periods. Most families are subsistence peasant farmers.  The main hazards in these communities are related to food insecurity, drought, landslides, and flooding.  As a result, these communities suffer from low productivity of staple crops and livestock, and lack employment to increase income. The project aims to improve economic productive activities, acquiring and developing capacities and knowledge and organization that will lead to integral economic and human development. The overall purpose of Caritas in this topic is to work in building human capacity and awareness, monitoring, analysis and forecasting of hazards, and people-centered early warning systems to be prepared and have better skills and knowledge to face climate change at the community level. The project will promote organic agriculture, water harvesting in big scale and the distribution of agricultural tools. The social crisis happening across the country has increased social insecurity and rural poverty levels, and thousands of people have migrated out of the country. The strengthening of grassroots organizations is important for sustainability. One cooperative will be strengthened to achieve sustainability and promote access to financial and technical assistance.</narrative>
  </description>
